ype":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>masoun</i> ‘mason, stone worker, builder in stone’ (Old Central French <i>maçon</i>, <i>masson</i>). A Middle English form <i>machun</i> (derived from Old French <i>machun</i>) gives rise to   Machin   and its variants. See also   Mayson  . Stonemasonry was a hugely important craft in the Middle Ages.","Italian (Veneto): variant of   Masone  .","Altered form of French   Masson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Masson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Lucien, Alain, Henri, Pierre, Yves, Agathe, Aime, Cecile, Clovis, Francois, Francoise.","Scottish: variant of   Mason   ‘mason’.","Scottish: variant of   Meston  ."]},{"name":"Machin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Juan, Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Mario, Miguel, Pedro, Blanca, Diego, Luis, Ramon.","English: variant of   Machen  . This is the more common form of the name in Britain and Ireland.","Spanish (<b>Machín</b>): probably a nickname from <i>machín</i> ‘boor, lout’, often applied to a blacksmith's apprentice."]},{"name":"Macon","meanings":["French: habitational name from any of several places so called, e.g. in Saône-et-Loire.","French: from the old oblique form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Mako</i>, a variant of <i>Mago</i>, a short form of compound names formed with <i>maht</i> ‘strength, power’ as the first element.","French (<b>Maçon</b>): occupational name for a mason, (Old) French <i>maçon</i>."]},{"name":"Machen","meanings":["English: variant of   Mason  , from the Middle English form <i>machun</i> (derived from Old French <i>machun</i>)."]},{"name":"Meason","meanings":["English: variant of   Mason  ."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs George Mason was born about 1495, in England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with George Mason."},"et":{"about 1495–":"umbes 1495–Surnud","1491–Male":"1491–Surnud","1518–1565":"1518–1565","1495–Female":"1495–Surnud","1565":"1565","1495":"1495","about 1495":"umbes 1495","1518":"1518","1491":"1491","Of Smethcote, Myddle, Shropshire, England":"Myddle, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1495–":"noin 1495–Kuollut","1491–Male":"1491–Kuollut","1518–1565":"1518–1565","1495–Female":"1495–Kuollut","1565":"1565","1495":"1495","about 1495":"noin 1495","1518":"1518","1491":"1491","Of Smethcote, Myddle, Shropshire, England":"Myddle, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1495–":"environ 1495–Décédée","1491–Male":"1491–Décédé","1518–1565":"1518–1565","1495–Female":"1495–Décédée